{{Refimprove|date=October 2011}} [[Image:FaultGouge.JPG|thumb|Salmon-colored fault gouge and associated fault separates two different rock types on the left (dark grey) and right (light grey). From the [[Gobi]] of [[Mongolia]].]] '''Fault gouge''' is a [[tectonite]] (a [[rock (geology)|rock]] formed by tectonic forces) with a very small grain size. Fault gouge has no [[Cohesion (geology)|cohesion]] and it is normally an [[consolidation (soil)|unconsolidated]] rock type, unless [[Cementation (geology)|cementation]] took place at a later stage. A fault gouge forms in the same way as [[fault breccia]], the latter also having larger [[clast]]s.<ref>Twiss, R.J. & Moores, E.M., 2000 (6th edition): ''Structural Geology'', W.H. Freeman & co, {{ISBN|0-7167-2252-6}}; p. 55</ref> In comparison to fault breccia, which is another incohesive fault rock, fault gouge has less visible fragments (less than 30% visible fragments regarding fault gouges, and more than 30% regarding fault breccia).<ref name="Sibson1977">{{cite journal | url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/content/133/3/191 | title=Fault rocks and fault mechanisms | author=Sibson, R. H. | journal=Journal of the Geological Society of London | year=1977 | volume=133 | pages=191â213 | doi=10.1144/gsjgs.133.3.0191}}</ref>
Gouge-filled faults can be weak planes in rock masses. If compressive stresses are enough these can cause compressive yielding or eventually rock fracture. <ref>Bertuzzi, R., 2015: ''Tunnel Support Loading Mechanism'', UNSW, Sydney, Australia; p. 1</ref>
==Origin== Fault gouge forms by tectonic movement along a localized zone of [[brittle deformation]] (a [[fault (geology)|fault zone]]) in a rock. The grinding and milling that results when the two sides of the fault zone move along each other results in a material that is made of loose fragments. First a fault breccia will form, but if the grinding continues the rock becomes fault gouge.
==See also== *[[Shale Gouge Ratio]] (SGR) *[[Fault breccia]] *[[Fault (geology)]]
