{{Taxobox | name = Scarlet badis | image = Scarlet_badis_male_1.jpg | image_width = 250px | image_caption = ''Dario dario'' male | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Chordata]] | classis = [[Actinopterygii]] | ordo = [[Perciformes]] | familia = [[Badidae]] | genus = ''[[Dario (genus)|Dario]]'' | species = '''''D. dario''''' | binomial = ''Dario dario'' | binomial_authority = ([[Francis Buchanan-Hamilton|F. Hamilton]], 1822) }}
The '''scarlet badis''' (''Dario dario'') is a [[tropical]] [[freshwater fish]] and one of the smallest known [[Percoidea|percoid]] fish species.<ref>{{FishBase | genus = Dario | species = dario | month = November | year = 2014 }}</ref><ref>http://www.seriouslyfish.com/profile.php?genus=Dario&species=dario&id=41</ref> It is a micropredator, feeding on small aquatic crustaceans, worms, insect larvae and other [[zooplankton]]. It is sold under a variety of names (''Badis badis bengalensis'', ''B. bengalensis'') in the aquarium trade.{{citation needed|date = September 2014}}
==Description== [[Image:Scarlet badis female.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Scarlet badis female|Scarlet badis female]] Scarlet badis are among the smallest percoid fish species. Males usually do not exceed {{convert|2|cm|in|abbr=on}}{{citation needed|date = September 2014}}, with the females being even smaller around {{convert|1.3|cm|in|abbr=on}}{{Citation needed|date = September 2014}}. Apart from the size difference, the sexes are easy to distinguish by the vibrant colors and prominent fins of the male.
==Distribution and habitat== The distribution of this species appears to be restricted to tributary systems draining into the [[Brahmaputra River]] in parts of [[West Bengal]] and [[Assam]] states of [[India]],{{citation needed|date = September 2014}} although it might also range into [[Bhutan]].{{citation needed|date = September 2014}} It typically inhabits shallow, clear water streams with sand or gravel substrates and dense growths of marginal and/or aquatic vegetation.
==Care in the Aquarium== The scarlet badis is becoming increasingly popular as an aquarium fish, particularly in [[Nano aquarium|nano aquaria]]. Their territorial nature does however mean that their environment must contain sufficient boundaries to prevent aggressive behaviour, especially between males of the species. The careful aquarist would ensure that the tank is sufficiently filled with items of decoration capable of breaking up lines of sight and establishing territories. natural driftwood or coconut shells used as caves are all ideal.<ref>http://aquariumsandfishes.com/429/keeping-scarlet-badis-dario-dario/</ref>
This species should only be considered for inclusion in an established and well-cycled aquarium with suitable water parameters.
